<subSubSection id="0DFA65634A7BE00AFF5CFE4FFB3DFD2B" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph id="455F36E84A7BE00AFF5CFE4FFB3DFD2B" blockId="23.[151,1437,358,709]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis id="7794EAFA4A7BE00AFF5CFE4FFE9BFE03" bold="true" box="[199,315,467,493]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species is deep fuscous with numerous, small ochraceous markings on the elytra and prominent ochraceous spots on the middle of the costa. The aedeagus has six prominent, subapical teeth on the dorsal surface and a long, subapical process with several teeth apically (
<figureCitation id="DDDB2A6D4A7BE00AFCBAFD87FCDDFDDB" box="[801,893,539,565]" captionStart="FIGURES 37" captionStartId="72.[151,264,1973,1998]" captionTargetBox="[191,1407,191,1927]" captionTargetId="figure@72.[161,1427,166,1954]" captionTargetPageId="72" captionText="FIGURES 37 A–H. Olidiana serra (Neilson), male genitalia.A.Aedeagus, dorsal view; B &amp; C. Aedeagus, lateral view; D. Subgenital plate, dorsal view; E. Style, dorsal view; F. Connective, dorsal view; G. Pygofer, ventral view; H. Pygofer, lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3366618/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Figs. 37</figureCitation>
A–B). Photographs of the male pygofer and aedeagus of the 
<typeStatus id="9A5B884A4A7BE00AFEAFFDA3FE36FDB7" box="[308,406,575,601]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">holotype</typeStatus>
male (
<collectingRegion id="8724F80A4A7BE00AFE7AFDA3FDF4FDB7" box="[481,596,575,601]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">California</collectingRegion>
Academy of Sciences, 
<collectingCountry id="3DF776784A7BE00AFCC0FDA3FC08FDB7" box="[859,936,575,601]" name="United States of America" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">U.S.A.</collectingCountry>
) were examined. They are identical with the specimen illustrated here. 
<bibRefCitation id="21714B194A7BE00AFE21FDFFFDC2FD93" author="Nielson, M. W." box="[442,610,611,637]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="1 - 318" refId="ref38619" refString="Nielson, M. W. (1982) A revision of the subfamily Coelidiinae (Homoptera: Cicadellidae) IV. Coelidiini. Pacific Insects Monograph, 38, 1 - 318." type="journal article" year="1982">Nielson (1982)</bibRefCitation>
over looked the presence of caudoventral processes and wrote “Pygofer in lateral aspect without caudoventral or caudodorsal processes”. However, in the ventral view caudoventral processes are very evident. This species was overlooked in the revision of the tribe by 
<bibRefCitation id="21714B194A7BE00AFC76FD37FB39FD2B" author="Nielson, M. W." box="[1005,1177,682,709]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="1 - 202" refId="ref38859" refString="Nielson, M. W. (2015) A revision of the tribe Coelidiini of the Oriental, Palearctic and Australian biogeographical regions (Hemiptera: Cicadellidae: Coelidiinae). Insecta Mundi, 0410, 1 - 202." type="book chapter" year="2015">Nielson (2015)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
